From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: tsf-sync contributors <tsf-sync@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Tue, 1 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 2/3] wifi: mt76: add KUnit tests for PTP hardware clock

Table-driven KUnit tests for the mt76 PTP clock conversion logic.
802.11 TSF counters use microseconds; PTP uses nanoseconds and
timespec64. The conversion must handle boundary conditions,
truncation from nanosecond to microsecond quantization, and signed
delta arithmetic for adjtime operations.

Test suites:

  mt76_ptp_conversion:
    - gettime:  TSF µs → timespec64 (10 parameterized cases)
    - settime:  timespec64 → TSF µs (13 parameterized cases)
    - adjtime:  read-modify-write delta (17 parameterized cases)
    - roundtrip: set then get, quantization loss (8 parameterized cases)
    - adjfine:  fixed-oscillator no-op contract
    - quantization bound: loss < 1 µs for all inputs (sweep)
    - sub-µs no-op: delta in (-999..999) ns leaves TSF unchanged (sweep)

  mt76_ptp_ops:
    - mock-based PTP ops with fake tsf_read/tsf_write
    - gettime reads TSF and converts correctly
    - settime converts and writes correctly
    - adjtime read-modify-writes correctly
    - adjfine returns 0 for any input
    - gettime/settime/adjtime return -EOPNOTSUPP when ops missing
    - read-only ops: settime/adjtime are NULL, gettime works
    - init with NULL ptp_ops: no clock registered
    - registration populates ptp_info function pointers correctly

Total: 48+ parameterized cases, 9 mock-based cases, 2 sweep tests.

The same conversion formulas are used by all WiFi PTP driver patches
(ath9k, ath10k, mt76, rtw88, rtw89), so these tests validate the
shared mathematical foundation.

Signed-off-by: tsf-sync contributors <tsf-sync@users.noreply.github.com>
